# Escape Apostrophes and Quotes in JSX/HTML

## Context
Our linter flags un-escaped apostrophes (`'`) and quotation marks (`"`) that appear **inside JSX/HTML text nodes**.  For example, writing:

```tsx
<h2>AI Power Users' Biggest Frustration—<span>Solved</span></h2>
```
triggers the warning:

```
' can be escaped with &apos;, &lsquo;, &#39;, &rsquo;.
```

## Rule
When generating JSX/HTML (including Markdown that _will_ be rendered as HTML), **never place raw apostrophes or quotation marks directly inside a text node**.  Instead, do **one** of the following:

1. **Use the corresponding HTML entity**
   • Apostrophe → `&rsquo;`, `&apos;`, or `&#39;`  
   • Double quote → `&quot;`, `&ldquo;`, or `&#34;`

2. **Embed the string inside a JavaScript expression** and rely on normal string escaping:

```tsx
<h2>{"AI Power Users' Biggest Frustration—"}<span>Solved</span></h2>
```

3. **Rewrite the sentence** to avoid the problematic character if it does not change the meaning.

## Examples
| ❌ Bad | ✅ Good |
|-------|--------|
| `<p>Sarah's workflow</p>` | `<p>Sarah&rsquo;s workflow</p>` |
| `<blockquote>"Time-saving" tools.</blockquote>` | `<blockquote>&ldquo;Time-saving&rdquo; tools.</blockquote>` |
| `<h2>AI Power Users' Biggest Frustration—</h2>` | `{"AI Power Users' Biggest Frustration—"}` |

## Checklist for the Assistant
- [ ] Scan all JSX/HTML text nodes for `'` and `"` characters.
- [ ] Apply one of the approved escaping strategies above.
- [ ] Ensure linter passes without string-literal escape warnings.

Follow this rule consistently in all future code generations. 
